
System Design Standard

A naming convention is a set of rules to follow when naming tables and columns in SQL.

General Rules 

- Never use SQL reserved keywords(e.g. select, table, user) as identifiers.
If an entity is a user, name the table dim_user or account to avoid syntax errors and the need for brackets or double quotes
Also decide which language is used.

- No Special Characters: Avoid spaces, hyphens, or dots in names. Stick strictly to alphanumeric characters and underscores to
  ensure compatibility across different SQL engines.

- Case sensitivity: snake_case is standard use for SQL database 

- Bronze Rules 
  All names must start with the source system name, and table names must match their original names without remaining 
  sourcesystem: Name of the source system, like Meta or Google. Entity is the table name as it is in the source system 
  source_system_entity example google_paid_ad

- Silver Rules
  All names must start with the source system name, and table names must match their original names without remaining 
  sourcesystem: Name of the source system, like Meta or Google. Entity is the table name as it is in the source system 
  source_system_entity example google_paid_ad

- Gold Rules 
  All names must use meaningful, business-aligned names for tables, starting with a category prefix.
  category_entity 
  Category: Describes the role of the table, such as dim for dimensions or fact fact table
  Entity: Descriptive name of the table, aligned with business domain (e.g. products, sales, clicks).
    Example: dim_sales, fact_clickcost
      dim_ for dimension
      fact_ for fact
      agg_ for aggregated tables 

- Surrogate Keys
  All primary keys in dimension tables must use the suffix _key 
    table_name_key It refers to the name of the table, and the key indicates the column is a surrogate key. Like session_id_key 

-Technical Columns 
  All technical columns must start with the prefix dwh_ followed by a descriptive name indicating the purpose of the column 
    Like dwh_load_date a system-generated column to store the date when the record was loaded.

-Stored Procedures
  All stored procedures used for loading data must follow the naming pattern load_layer
  layer refers to bronze, silver, and gold.
  Example load_silver  a stored procedure for loading data into the silver layer
